english:
  title: Record of the Ink Bamboo Screen in the Hall of the Lingying Garrison
  author: An Chuk
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The human heart, dwelling within itself and untouched by the external world, remains luminous and unmoved, secure in its essence. Only when things of the world encounter us does the heart stir within and manifest without. What moves our heart through contact with objects are the faculties of ear, eye, mouth, and nose—yet the eye's domain is broadest of all. Among all things that touch us, some stir us rightly, while others shake us wrongly. Only the sage responds to things with the Way intact, losing not what is right. Common people, by contrast, shift with each encounter, their paths diverging endlessly. Thus the worthy of old, desiring to rectify their hearts, were ever cautious in their daily dealings with things—and most especially careful in what they chose for their eyes. Some gazed upon crystal ice to contemplate purity; others wore cord and leather to emulate their suppleness and resilience. All sought to guard the outer form and cultivate the inner nature.

    Lingying, a great garrison of the eastern lands, lacked proper screens to grace its halls, leaving them bare and austere. I obtained several bolts of fine silk and commissioned the recluse Geomsan to paint a twelve-fold screen of ink bamboo. Yet this was not merely to furnish a curious ornament or hide the austerity of the place. There is deeper purpose here.

    Consider bamboo: it is pure, free from entanglement; steadfast, unchanging; hollow, yet spacious; straight, asking nothing of others. No worthy man or woman of any age has failed to love it. Wang Ziyou once asked, "How could I endure a single day without this gentleman?" Such is the affection it commands. Seek its parallel in human nature, and you find one in Boyi. Mencius said, "Those who hear the way of Boyi become incorruptible though once greedy, resolute though once weak." Even a hundred generations hence, merely hearing of his virtue, men are thus transformed—how much more so when morning and evening we see it with our eyes and feel its presence?

    Let all who sit before this screen in this hall henceforth see in bamboo's clarity a means to cherish integrity without burdening the people; in its steadfastness, a strength to uphold righteousness unmoved; in its hollowness, a capacity to embrace all without harshness; in its straightness, a courage to stand alone, unbending to the times. Such is how bamboo stirs the human spirit. Is not this screen, then, a blessing for all people?

    Those who gaze upon this bamboo and gain this understanding are fortunate indeed. But those who see it and do not—let them read this record.
  footnotes:
    - Wang Ziyou (王子猷) was a fourth-century Chinese gentleman famous for his love of bamboo; this quotation became proverbial for devotion to virtue.
    - Boyi (伯夷) was a legendary sage of ancient China whose moral example inspired virtue across generations—here used as the human equivalent to the bamboo's spiritual influence.
    - The 'garrison' (鎭營) refers to a military administrative center; Lingying was likely a strategic post in Korea during An Chuk's time.
